  "prompt": "Why don't cars have scallops, like golf balls, for fuel efficiency?",
  "response": "While golf balls have dimples to reduce air resistance and improve aerodynamics, simply adding scallops or dimples to cars would not necessarily improve fuel efficiency in the same way. Here's why:\n\n1. Golf ball dimples work by creating a thin layer of air that clings to the ball's surface, reducing drag. This effect is most pronounced at the ball's relatively low speeds.\n\n2. Cars move at much higher speeds and have different aerodynamic considerations. The shape, smoothness, and overall design of a car's body are more critical for reducing air resistance.\n\n3. Modern cars are already designed with aerodynamics in mind, using wind tunnel testing and computational fluid dynamics to optimize their shape.\n\n4. Adding scallops or dimples to a car's surface could actually increase turbulence and drag, potentially reducing fuel efficiency.\n\nInstead, car manufacturers focus on:\n- Streamlined body designs\n- Reducing frontal area\n- Smooth underbody surfaces\n- Active aerodynamic features like adjustable spoilers\n- Lightweight materials\n\nThese approaches are more effective for improving a car's fuel efficiency than adding surface irregularities.",
